One way to see this is to use Cantor's diagonal argument. We can try to enumerate the countable ordinals as $\{\alpha_0, \alpha_1, \ldots\}$, and then construct a new ordinal $\alpha$ that is strictly greater than each $\alpha_i$. In other words, we want $\alpha$ to be an element of every set $S_n = \{\beta: \beta > \alpha_i \text{ for all } i < n\}$ for $n = 0, 1, 2, \ldots$. Such an $\alpha$ would have to be larger than every $\alpha_i$, so it couldn't be in the list.

Let's see how to construct such an $\alpha$:

• Let $\alpha_0$ be the smallest ordinal greater than $\alpha_0$ (which exists because there are no smallest ordinals). (More precisely, let $\alpha_0 = \omega + 1$, where $\omega$ is the first infinite ordinal.)

• Let $\alpha_1$ be the smallest ordinal greater than both $\alpha_0$ and $\alpha_1$.

• Let $\alpha_2$ be the smallest ordinal greater than $\alpha_0, \alpha_1$, and $\alpha_2$.

And so on. It's not hard to see that $\alpha = \sup\{\alpha_n\}$ is an ordinal that is greater than each $\alpha_i$.

The punchline is that $\alpha$ is countable, since it's the supremum of a countable set of countable ordinals. But it's not on our list, so our list wasn't complete.

